snai</i> ‘oak grove’. Compare   Chenette   and   Chenier   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Chenette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Armand.","Altered form of French Canadian <b>Chenet</b>, itself an (intermediate) altered form of   Cheney   3. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>.","History: The (majority of the) Chenettes are descendants of Bertrand Chesnay/Chenay <i>dit</i>/<i>sieur</i> de La Garenne from Brittany (France); see   Cheney  ."]},{"name":"Chaney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Cheney was born about 1460, in Waltham Abbey, Essex, England. He had at least 1 son. He died about 1500, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"about 1460–about 1500":"umbes 1460–umbes 1500","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","about 1500":"umbes 1500","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","about 1460":"umbes 1460","Waltham Abbey, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, England"},"fi":{"about 1460–about 1500":"noin 1460–noin 1500","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","about 1500":"noin 1500","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","about 1460":"noin 1460","Waltham Abbey, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, England"},"fr":{"about 1460–about 1500":"environ 1460–environ 1500","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","about 1500":"environ 1500","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","about 1460":"environ 1460","Waltham Abbey, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Cheney est né environ 1460, à Waltham Abbey, Essex, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé environ 1500, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 42 ans."},"de":{"about 1460–about 1500":"um 1460–um 1500","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","about 1500":"um 1500","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","about 1460":"um 1460","Waltham Abbey, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, England","lifeSummary":"Robert Cheney wurde um 1460 in Waltham Abbey, Essex, England geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb um 1500 im Alter von 42 Jahren in seinem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"about 1460–about 1500":"about 1460–about 1500","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1460–1500":"1460–1500","1500":"1500","1542":"1542","about 1500":"about 1500","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","about 1460":"about 1460","Waltham Abbey, Essex, England":"Waltham